history.acquisition: In Gonville and Caius College by 1600, when it was recorded as no. 74 in the Ecloga Oxonio-Cantabrigiensis by Thomas James (1600). It is recorded as no. 1006 in Bernard's Catalogi Manuscriptorum Angliae et Hiberniae (1697). The College's classmarks '200' and '106' printed on labels in red and black ink on the spine and written in red and black ink on labels pasted on the inside of the upper cover, together with the College's armorial bookplate.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description provided by M. R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the manuscripts in the library of Gonville and Caius College (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1907).

seg.note: The flyleaves are made from leaves from another manuscript. These have been folded in half and bound into the manuscript at their fold. Two such leaves were folded to create four endleaves at the front of the manuscript; all but the first have been cut out. One leaf was folded to create two endleaves at the back of the manuscript; both remain. The measurements of the dimensions of the leaves given here are those of the leaves as they currently occur in the manuscript and not those of the original unfolded leaves. Since these leaves have probably been cropped it is not possible to reconstruct their original measurements.

layout.note: The dimensions of the text space that are here given are based on measurements of the height and width of the double columns on the original unfolded leaves. Since pp. 215-218 form a complete original leaf and the text on it has not been affected by cropping it is possible to give the dimensions of the original text space.

collation.note: Since this collation refers to the first bifolium as quire 1 instead of 'a2' the quire numbers differ from those that have been added to the manuscript in pencil and those used by M.R. James. The collation also differs from James's in that it considers quire 7 [James's quire 6] a quaternion with an added leaf rather than a quinterion with a cancelled leaf.

provenance.p: A member of the Pympe familyPympe family in the first half of the 16th century owned or accessed this part of the manuscript: their family name inscribed in the lower margin of p. 35 hyldy[r]sam Pympe, Pympe est arma, and Pympe the lower margin of p. 46: Pympe. The inscription hyld[r]sam may refer to the village of Hildersham in Cambridgeshire.
